SIMPLE: reconciliation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reconciliation
<hw>Rec`on*cil`i*a"tion</hw> <pr>(-s?l`?*?"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧conciliation</ets>, L.
<ets>reconciliatio</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
reconciling, or the state of being reconciled; reconcilement;
restoration to harmony; renewal of friendship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Reconciliation</qex> and friendship with God really form the
basis of all rational and true enjoyment.</q> <rj><qau>S.
Miller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Reduction to congruence or consistency; removal of
inconsistency; harmony.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A clear and easy <qex>reconciliation</qex> of those seeming
inconsistencies of Scripture.</q> <rj><qau>D. Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Reconcilement; reunion; pacification;
appeasement; propitiation; atonement; expiation.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reconciliatory</ent>⟦br⟧
